@medlar_ Logic has had Match EQ for years but it's kinda wild haha, some of the iZotope stuff 'listens' to sources and uses AI to come up with parameters on compressors etc. you could always 'listen' to a reference, save it as a preset and then use it on yours. Could actually be cool!

@raihan_ @water_and_music but if someone gave me a sample pack, I'm still not that artist. There's still a million other variables to factor in that make up someone's art. but the more those nebulous variables can be identified and applied by AI or ML, the gap shortens 👀 🙃 🔮 🕵🏻‍♂️💀

@raihan_ @water_and_music it's a thin line in music for sure - sample packs are a good example of that. it's clearly trying to be an artist but it's not a sample or a publishing issue. but it's clearly 'in the style of'. ML will soon facilitate that at a granular level, as well as combinations of styles
yes, this is what I'm doing at half 4 on a Friday in 32 degrees sunshine 🙃

I love the idea of using ML to 'take' the mix or mastering traits of an engineer and apply them to your own mix. This can't do that (well) yet, but it's the first time I've seen it being done so blatantly (and super fast), but it's also a slippery slope

From what I've tried the results are pretty bad, but a concept we discussed in our @water_and_music AI feature not too long ago. What if you 'sampled' the tonal balance, dynamic range and loudness of a track, but not the music itself? Is it still copyright infringement?

This is wild. It's a free AI mastering tool (like LANDR) but you can also upload your own reference track, OR you can select a track you want your master to sound like from their list including Daft Punk, Donna Summer, Toto, Jay Z, there's hundreds

For now, it seems anyone is free to data mine copyrighted content to create a model that they then sell as a product without anyone's permission. @UK_Music is already on it with a statement and a campaign against this decision. Interesting to see how it goes...!

..for the future of IP protection around AI modelling in music. One of the caveats and potential protections many of us have been saying is that in the future artists will receive a form of royalty when their music or likeness is used in a model. This implies that won't happen.

"Some in the creative industries also use TDM and AI to understand their market or create new works – they will also see benefits". This exception was introduced back in 2014 but it was a very different time. This feels like a reckless decision that sets a dangerous tone..
Key quotes: "The benefits will be reducing the time needed to obtain permission from multiple rights holders and no licence fee to pay. This will speed up the TDM process and development of AI" and..

Last week the UK govt released a report on AI and data mining around copyrighted content, concluding that "The govt has decided to introduce a new copyright and database right exception which allows TDM (text and data mining) for any purpose"
